Prey and predator relationship

A prey and predator relationship in a terrestrial ecosystem was relatively well reported and mathematically modeled.

Cf. That in an aquatic ecosystem is not so obvious because a multi-species relationship in an aquatic ecosystem tends to be in a food web rather than in a food chain.

Lotka-Volterr’s prey-predator system

One of the most famous prey-predator models is Lotka-Volterra’s model.

\[\frac{dN_t}{dt} = a\cdot N_t - b\cdot N_t\cdot P_t= N_t \cdot (a-b\cdot P_t)\]

\[\frac{dP_t}{dt} = c \cdot P_t\cdot N_t - d\cdot P_t= P_t \cdot (c\cdot N_t-d)\]

where \(N_t\) = a population size of a prey species at time t, and

\(P_t\) = a population size of a predator species at time t.

a, b, c, and d are positive constants.

A non-dimensional form of the original Lotka-Volterr’s prey-predator system

By \(u \equiv \frac{cN_t}{d}\), \(v \equiv \frac{bP_t}{a}\), \(\tau \equiv at\), \(\alpha \equiv \frac{d}{a}\)

\[\begin{equation} \tag{1} \frac{du_\tau}{d\tau} = u_\tau(1-v_\tau) \end{equation}\]

\[\begin{equation} \tag{2} \frac{dv_\tau}{d\tau} = \alpha v_\tau(u_\tau-1) \end{equation}\]

Solving the system (eqs. 1 and 2) for \(u_\tau\) and \(v_\tau\): a numerical approxmiation

The system (eqs. 1 and 2) cannot be analytically solved. Instead, several numerical methods had been used.

To convince students of how to numerically solve a system that consists of differential equations, I introduce two methods:
(1) Euler method
(2) Modified Euler method, which is universally accepted.

A numerical approximation: Euler method

Consider a general differential equation \[\frac{dY_t}{dt} = f(Y_t)\]

where \(Y_t\) = a quantity that varies over time t; \(t\) = time; and \(f(Y_t)\) is an arbitrary function.

Approximation by Euler method:

\[\begin{align} Y_{a+\Delta t} &\approx Y_a + {\left.\frac{dY_t}{dt}\right|}_{t=a}\cdot \Delta t \\ \\ &= Y_a + f(Y_a)\cdot \Delta t \end{align}\]

A graphic illustration of Euler method

A graphic illustration of Euler method

Euler method for a non-dimensional form of Lotka-Volterra model (eqs. 1 and 2)

LV.f=function(u1=1.5, v1=1.5, a=1, dt=0.2, iter)  {
  #Using Euler method; 
  u=c(); 
  v=c();
  u[1]=u1; 
  v[1]=v1;
  #
  for(i in 1:iter)   {
    u[i+1]=u[i]+u[i]*(1-v[i])*dt;
    v[i+1]=v[i]+a*v[i]*(u[i]-1)*dt; 
  };
  return(data.frame(u,v));
};

A numerical approximation: Modified Euler method (aka Runge-Kutta method)

Consider a general differential equation \[\frac{dY_t}{dt} = f(Y_t)\]

where \(Y_t\) = a quantity that varies over time t; \(t\) = time; and \(f(Y_t)\) is an arbitrary function.

Approximation by Euler method:

\[\begin{align} Y_{a+\Delta t} &\approx Y_a + \frac{1}{2}\cdot \left[ \left.\frac{dY_t}{dt} \right|_{t=a} + \left. \frac{dY_t}{dt} \right|_{t=a+\Delta t} \right] \cdot \Delta t \\ \\ &= Y_a + \frac{1}{2}\left[ f(Y_a) + f(Y_{a+\Delta t}) \right] \cdot \Delta t \end{align}\]

Modified Euler method for a non-dimensional form of Lotka-Volterra model (eqs. 1 and 2)

#modified Euler method
LV1.f=function(u1 = 0.5, v1 = 0.5, a = 1, dt = 0.1, iter = iteration)  {
  u <- c();  
  v <- c();
  f1<-c(); 
  f2<-c();
  
  u[1] <- u1; 
  v[1] <- v1;
  
  for(i in 1:iter)   {
    f1[i] <- u[i]*(1-v[i])
    f2[i] <- a*v[i]*(u[i]-1)
    
    u[i+1] <- u[i] + f1[i]*dt
    v[i+1] <- v[i] + f2[i]*dt
    
    f1[i+1] <- u[i+1]*(1-v[i+1])
    f2[i+1] <- a*v[i+1]*(u[i+1]-1)
    
    u[i+1] <- u[i] + dt*( f1[i] + f1[i+1] )/2
    v[i+1] <- v[i] + dt*( f2[i] + f2[i+1] )/2
  }
  #
  return(data.frame(u, v));
};
